SIMPLE: phalanx
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phalanx
<hw>Pha"lanx</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Phalanxes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L. <plw>Phalanges</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., from Gr. <grk>fa`lagx</grk>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Gr. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A body of heavy-armed infantry
formed in ranks and files close and deep. There were several different
arrangements, the phalanx varying in depth from four to twenty-five or
more ranks of men.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In cubic <xex>phalanx</xex> firm
advanced.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Grecian <qex>phalanx</qex>, moveless as a tower.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any body of troops or men formed in close array, or
any combination of people distinguished for firmness and solidity of a
union.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At present they formed a united <qex>phalanx</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sheep recumbent, and the sheep that grazed,⟦br⟧
All huddling into <qex>phalanx</qex>, stood and gazed.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A Fourierite community; a phalanstery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>One of the digital bones of the
hand or foot, beyond the metacarpus or metatarsus; an
internode.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[<ets>pl</ets>. <er>Phalanges</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A group or bundle of stamens, as in polyadelphous
flowers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phalarope</ent>⟦br⟧
